-----------ALGO WITH Example-------------
Algorithm: Majority Element (Boyer–Moore Voting Algorithm)

Problem:
Find the element that appears more than ⌊n/2⌋ times in the array.

Idea:
Maintain a candidate element and a counter.
If the current element matches the candidate → increase count.
If it is different → decrease count.
When count becomes negative, choose the current element as the new candidate.

Steps:
1. Initialize:
      ele = nums[0]   (candidate element)
      c = 0           (counter)

2. Traverse the array:
      For each element x in nums

      a) If x == ele
             increase counter (c += 1)

      b) Else
             decrease counter (c -= 1)

      c) If counter becomes negative
             change candidate:
             ele = x
             c = 1

3. After traversal, ele will be the majority element.

Return ele.


Example:

nums = [2,2,1,1,1,2,2]

Step-by-step table

Index | Element | Candidate (ele) | Count (c)
----------------------------------------------
Start |   -     | 2               | 0

0     |   2     | 2               | 1
1     |   2     | 2               | 2
2     |   1     | 2               | 1
3     |   1     | 2               | 0
4     |   1     | 1               | 1
5     |   2     | 1               | 0
6     |   2     | 2               | 1


Final Majority Element:
2


Why this works:
Majority element appears more than n/2 times,
so it cannot be completely cancelled out by other elements.


Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
